name: Coro Val Biois
comments: The birth of the Val Biois Choir dates back to 1971 by the then parish priest of Caviola, Don Cesare Vazza. It is currently made up of 26 choristers who come from the villages of the homonymous valley and has been directed since 1976 by maestro Attilio Costa. Over the years the choir has carried out an appreciated choral activity performing in numerous Italian and some foreign locations. He is the interpreter of a repertoire that includes popular and mountain songs with a preference for author songs. In 1987 he recorded the LP "Sol inte la Val del Biois", in 2003 the CD entitled "Le Zime dell'Auta" and finally in 2006 the CD entitled "Coro Val Biois" offering the most significant pieces of the repertoire.

name: Coro Genzianella
comments: Coro Genzianella di Trento was born in 1950 thanks to the passion of 9 friends who love singing and is one of the oldest male choirs from Trentino with mountain repertoire. In 1961 they shortened their name to "Coro Genzianella". Numerous performances have seen the choir as protagonist over the years through concerts and reviews in various Italian regions and also abroad: Spain, Belgium, Germany, Romania and Scotland. After having recorded the first album "La Val di Fiemme" in the 70s, under the guidance of the master and composer Carlo Deflorian, in 1989 the Chorus recorded a new LP entitled "La Tera del nono" and in 2000, on the occasion of the 50th anniversary of its foundation, a CD "La Genzianella, 50 years of beautiful singing, emotions and friendship". Currently the Choir is made up of 29 elements and intends to carry on its activity in the conviction of the cultural validity of its message and in the awareness of the value that comes together in friendship for the serene effort of choral practice. Since 2008 it has been chaired by Andrea Trettel and since March 2014 it has been directed by Maestro Diego Cavada.

name: Howard Lucraft

He appeared regularly on the BBC before emigrating to the the Los Angeles area where he appeared on radio, composed and arranged for Stan Kenton, Anita O'Day, Ray Noble and others. He was a music editor for Daily Variety and had a jazz television show. He served as president of the Hollywood Press Club three times.

name: Coro Alpino Trentino di Gardolo
comments: In August 1949 the Negritella Choir was born, with maestro Alfeo Caracristi. In 1955, due to the unavailability of maestro Alfeo Caracristi, the choir ceased its activity until 1967, when a small group of these former choristers, suffering from the nostalgia and recharged with good will, began to make a choir again, in competition with some elements of the parish choir. In a few years it matures an artistic and human experience that allows it to achieve its first important successes, first in the neighboring municipalities, then outside the region and, in 1975, in Germany, with the first trip to Ludenscheid,  in the district of Dusseldorf, the desire to make new friends leads, in 1976, to a twinning with the mountaineering association DAV (Deutsche Alpenverein) of Altdorf, Bavaria. The following year the two associations met in Trentino on the occasion of a trip to the Brenta and, again in the same year, the Choir held another concert in Altdorf, officially signing the twinning, which has been going on for 46 years. exhibited in other important German cities: Cologne, Munich, Stuttgart and numerous locations in Bavaria, as well as 3 trips to Berlin. Since 2008 the Choir has also made itself known in Upper Austria with some successful tours. After 30 years of activity, in 1997, Alfeo Caracristi left the direction of the choir to Renzo Lazzeri and since 2003 the choir has been directed by Franco Tomasi, who has gained over thirty years of experience within the choir of Gardolo. From 1 October 2021 the direction of the choir has been entrusted to Maestro Roberto Deflorian. In the past he conducted the "Argentario di Cognola choir", the "Campel di Tavernaro choir", the "Dolomiti choir of Trento" and the "La Tor di Caldonazzo choir". In its history the choir has recorded two LPs: "We sing together in the mountains" and "T'Ho collection up there in the mountains" and in 2001 recorded a CD entitled "Storie cantade. The current choir president is Tiziano Mattedi.

name: Jaybird Coleman
comments: Blues musician. Born in Gainesville, Alabama, he learned to play the harmonica as a young boy, and he honed his skills as a musician while serving in the United States Army during World War I. After leaving the Army, he joined the Birmingham Jug Band and travelled with the "Rabbit Foot Minstrels" show. Coleman made his first recordings in 1927 on the Gennett, Silvertone, and Black Patti Record labels in Birmingham, Alabama. During the 1930's, he toured throughout Alabama, and he also made further recordings for the OKeh and Columbia Record labels in Atlanta, Georgia. Coleman's musical career declined during the late 1930's through the late 1940's. During the 1940's, he occassionally performed on the streets of Birmingham. He continued working outside of music and occasionally making street side performances until his death from cancer in 1950 at the age of 54.

name: William Steffe
comments: William Steffe was born in 1830 in South Carolina. Moving to Philadelphia, PA, he claimed to have composed a tune in 1855 or 1856 with the words, " Say Bummers, Will You Meet us ", with the traditional Glory Hallelujah refrain, for the Goodwill Fire Company of Philadelphia, PA, whose members were known as "Bummers". Though Steffe may have played a role in creating the "Say, Bummers" version of the song, which seems to be a variant of and owe a debt to both " Say Brothers, Will You Meet Us? " and " John Brown's Body " Steffe couldn't have written the "Glory Hallelujah" tune or the "Say, Brothers" text, both of which had been circulating for decades before his birth. In 1885, Richard J. Hinton, one of John Brown's biographers, wrote to Steffe asking about the circumstances of the writing of the original song. Steffe's four replies are contained in the archives of the Kansas State Historical Society in Topeka. On December 11th, 1885, Steffe wrote: "...though I never claimed any notoriety in music I want to prove by the best evidence the origin of the music of the popular song. Those who prompted me to write it are all 'gathered to their fathers' most of those who sang Say Brothers will you meet us-- are 'beyond the river'...." In his second and third letters, mailed more than a year later, Steffe stated that he sent a copy of the song to Hinton, but that since the copy was not received, it must have gotten lost in the mail. Steffe said he had trouble remembering the circumstances of the writing and was apparently in contact with others in Philadelphia who were present and could have testified that Steffe wrote the song. But Steffe never gave Hinton any verification from these other persons. In the last letter dated March 4, 1887, Steffe finally told the whole story of the writing of the song. He was asked to write it in 1855 or 56 for the Good Will Engine Company of Philadelphia. They used it as a song of welcome for the visiting Liberty Fire Company of Baltimore. The original verse for the song was "Say, Bummers, Will You Meet Us?" Someone else converted the "Say, Bummers" verse into the hymn "Say, Brothers, Will You Meet Us." He thought he might be able to identify that person, but was never able to do so. He also wrote that he had visited Boston during the Civil War while carrying dispatches from General Butler to Governor Andrew. While there, he attended a review of the "Tiger" Battalion. The "Tigers" sang "John Brown's Body," and, afterwards, Steffe told them he had originated the tune.

name: Milton "Lindberg" Sparks
comments: Milton "Lindberg" Sparks and his twin brother Aaron "Pinetop", were born in Corona, Lee County, Mississippi, to Sullie Gant and Ruth McWhorter. They later took the surname of their stepfather, Carl Sparks. In 1920, the family moved to St. Louis, where Pinetop had "rudimentary music education at school". He and his twin brother formed a group, with Aaron playing the piano in a boogie-woogie style and Marion singing.

name: Sparks Brothers
comments: Blues duo, consisting of singer Milton 'Lindberg' Sparks and singer and pianist Aaron 'Pinetop' Sparks. They recorded for Victor, Bluebird and Decca 1932-1935, and were also known as Pinetop and Lindberg. These artists were born Aaron and Marion Gant and acquired the name Sparks from a step-father. Marion Sparks subsequently changed his name to Milton around 1929, nonetheless Pinetop and Lindberg are identified in the Victor files as Aaron and Marion Sparks.
